<TEXT>
new england power officials warned on sunday night 
that blackouts may occur throughout the sixstate region monday 
unless businesses and homeowners conserve electricity amid the heat 
wave 
a shutdown this weekend of the maine yankee nuclear power plant 
and one of four power generators on salem harbor in massachusetts 
has worsened the already difficult power situation for most of new 
england officials said 
the national weather service reported that 18 cities in the 
northeastern quarter of the nation reported record high 
temperatures for the date sunday and forecast that new england 
would have 90s with 80s in the northern portions on monday 
boston had an ironic record low temperature of 78 late sunday 
afternoon when an ocean breeze cooled the area but as soon as the 
winds shifted the temperature shot up 14 degrees in 10 minutes 
the weather service said 
monday is definitely a very tight day said bill sheperdson 
a spokesman for the new england power pool which coordinates power 
supplies for utilities throughout new england 
if we dont get a considerable contribution by our customers 
as we did a number of days last week we may not be able to provide 
uninterrupted service sheperdson said 
boston edison spokesman michael monahan called the situation 
tremendously tight and said the numbers simply dont add up for 
power supply to continue without periodic controlled blackouts 
monday 
the new england region controlled by the new england power pool 
set a record for summertime power demand last thursday at 19608 
megawatts the pool is expecting demand to exceed 19900 megawatts 
monday 
thats 300 megawatts more plus youre missing maine yankee 
which is 860 megawatts monahan said 
maine yankee shut down over the weekend because of a transformer 
problem according to monahan the pool is predicting the plant 
will be out of service until wednesday at the earliest 
in new york city meanwhile consolidated edison reported a 
record for sunday electricity demand 7645 megawatts between 9 
pm and 10 pm breaking the record of 6770 megawatts set last 
sunday spokesman marty gitten said peak demand often occurs at 
that hour as people return home from weekend activities and turn on 
air conditioners and lights 
</TEXT>
