<TEXT>
not very long ago this resort spas 
illegal gambling was hotter than its muchtouted healing spring 
water so much so that local government winked and even reaped tax 
revenue rather than stop it 
throngs of tourists and townspeople took chances in violation 
of state law on at least 350 slot machines card games bingo and 
bookmaking 
police looked the other way except to collect the municipal 
amusement tax until 1967 when a state crackdown during the 
administration of the late gov winthrop rockefeller scrapped tons 
of betting devices 
it was probably the only illegal tax in this country collected 
by a city recalls state sen eugene bud canada who was 
garland county sheriff in 1967 but wasnt invited to join state 
agents who raided the casinos 
they built a city auditorium where the miss arkansas pageant 
is held a beautiful place and a city hall and the main 
firehouse downtown all on an illegal tax he says 
dusty tax records show the city levied 10 monthly for each slot 
machine 
the baxter hotel butlers barbecue harlem chicken shack and 
the eatmore cafe had one slot each more adventurous were the jd 
jackson fish market vfw club and hot springs country club with 
two slots apiece 
the best bet at coys steak house these days might be the 
forktender prime cuts but in 1967 diners waiting for a table 
could play eight slot machines 
tax rates ran 100 a month for bingo and cards 500 for large 
casinos those with more than five gaming tables and 300 for 
small casinos the casinos included places like the ohio club 
southern club and the vapors 
tax rates were raised in 1964 but the elks club refused to pay 
the difference records show club officials sent payments on their 
five slots at the old rate until the state raids in early fall 1967 
the cornerstone of public morality is respect for the law 
rockefeller declared that year in hiring former fbi agent lynn a 
davis to be state police chief 
davis says he told rockefeller he wanted to concentrate on law 
enforcement not politics and specifically on closing casinos he 
says rockefeller slapped his knee and said thats exactly what i 
want 
early on aug 17 1967 davis and about two dozen officers 
converged on the downtown bridge street club 
it was after normal business hours and the door was locked the 
owner was summoned according to newspaper accounts when he didnt 
show after an hour davis broke a glass panel in the door with a 
tire iron in front of photographers and troopers knocked in the 
door 
two days later the arkansas gazette editorialized davis has 
given the state the most convincing demonstration yet of how the 
state can break the back of the notorious hot springs gambling 
operation which has been a scandal of historic but nonetheless 
disgraceful dimension he was following his responsibility to 
the law where local enforcement had defaulted 
canada cried foul im really incensed the sheriff told 
reporters he complained about the lack of notice to local lawmen 
especially those who have to be elected and must answer to the 
people 
davis responded 21 years later the bridge street club the 
ohio club and all of the other clubs could be found by tourists who 
went to hot springs they could have been found by a blind man and 
if the sheriff didnt know they were there then i was afraid to 
take him with me on a raid 
canada attributes the friction to politics 
you had a brandnew republican governor and you had a 
brandnew democratic sheriff he says 
proposals to legalize casino gambling fell twice to voter 
rejection in 1964 and in 1984 and once to rockefellers veto in 
1967 
</TEXT>
