<TEXT>
communist guerrillas released four 
army officers and an enlisted man in this coconut farming village 
sunday after holding them hostage in the mountains for more than 
two months 
in another development machetewielding assailants hacked to 
death 14 villagers including three children near the central city 
of tacloban police said 
gregorio rosal spokesman for the communist new peoples army 
unlocked the chains from the five prisoners wrists in front of 170 
journalists relatives and officials waiting near a coconut grove 
on june 1 the rebels captured lts abraham casis oscar 
singson clarito santos and rommel salamanca and constabulatory 
sgt john jacob in this village about 70 miles southeast of manila 
in quezon province 
the five men dressed in civilian clothes were driving toward 
manila when they were abducted by rebels they thought were 
government troops according to col hernani figueroa a military 
spokesman rebels often wear uniforms similar to army fatigues 
the military and the rebels agreed to a temporary ceasefire 
that ends at noon tuesday 
provincial officials in quezon assured the rebels they will not 
force people to join government paramilitary units authorities 
also agreed to create a committee to investigate alleged human 
rights abuses by government soldiers and to pay damages to victims 
twelve suspected communists including a 71yearold woman were 
arrested in a raid in kilawis village on the outskirts of manila 
according to sgt romeo artajos 
firearms and documents were seized along with the suspects who 
were accused of recruiting members for the communist insurgency 
artajos said 
the official philippine news agency said the military on the 
central island of negros detained five suspected rebels in 
connection with the slaying of an australian businessmen in the 
province on monday 
the police chief in tacloban maj gabriel bardillon said six 
assailants some wearing masks attacked members of two families 
living in shanties along an abandoned golf course in the village of 
cabalawan about 350 miles southeast of manila 
maj bardillon said only five children survived the massacre 
shortly after midnight saturday and that police were searching for 
the attackers in the forests around the village 
he said the motive for the attack apparently was revenge over a 
personal grudge and that one of the survivors identified three of 
the killers as enemies of some of the victims 
