george bush is playing the vice president 
gambit for everything its worth which isnt very much but then 
its the only bit of show business available this week at the 
republican national convention 
his orchestrated surprise will be good theater for a few hours 
in new orleans and obviously the republican presidential 
nominees choice of a running mate is a crucial decision in the gop 
bid to keep the white house 
but nobody is going to remember the theatrics once they are done 
the bush plan is to announce the selection on thursday morning 
with tight secrecy until then campaign manager lee atwater said 
therell be as much drama as we can have the better to boost 
interest and television ratings 
im for doing anything that will help build up a tv 
audience atwater said 
there wont be any leaks of this one because im not gonna 
tell a soul said bush 
some souls may think there are clues however take gov james 
r thompson of illinois who telephoned bush on friday and asked 
not be considered for second spot on the ticket 
such requests often come from people who figure they arent 
going to be chosen anyhow 
having been there bush knows the way the game is played for 
bush there was a hotel suite across the street from the detroit 
convention hall in which president reagan was nominated in 1980 
bush a defeated rival for the republican nomination that year 
waited out a very long night of speculation that former president 
gerald r ford would be the vice presidential nominee on the reagan 
ticket it was going on midnight when that deal fell apart and 
reagan turned to bush a quick telephone call a quick acceptance 
a joint appearance before the convention to quell the chaos and 
introduce the running mate 
now it is bushs turn to issue the summons his presidential 
nomination is set the vice presidency is the only unfilled role 
actually what he is doing is choosing his candidate the 
oldfashioned way until relatively recent conventions 
presidential nominees observed strict vows of silence on the vice 
presidency until after their own nominations advance discussion 
was presumptuous gauche 
on wednesday night of convention week after the roll call that 
delivered the nomination the presidential nominee would summon his 
high command into latenight session to settle on no 2 prospects 
would come and go from the candidates suite 
in 1964 president lyndon b johnson chose sen hubert h 
humphrey for his ticket but summoned connecticut sen thomas j 
dodd too just to keep people guessing 
latterday candidates have taken to listing prospects in advance 
and in some cases to conducting preconvention job interviews 
they send out questionnaires they look at fitness reports 
that practice took on some urgency after the 1972 democratic 
convention at which nominee george mcgovern chose sen thomas 
eagleton to run with him and learned after the fact that eagleton 
had been hospitalized for nervous exhaustion and fatigue and had 
undergone electric shock treatments 
r sargent shriver replaced him on the ticket which went down 
in flames and presidential nominees have tended to conduct more 
thorough advance checks on prospective running mates ever since 
in 1976 jimmy carter interviewed seven prospects then chose 
walter f mondale for vice president when his turn came mondale 
conducted a similar set of preconvention auditions and chose rep 
geraldine ferraro 
democratic presidential nominee michael dukakis interviewed a 
halfdozen prospects then chose texas sen lloyd bentsen a week 
before the national convention that nominated that ticket in 
atlanta 
in the bush selection game a dozen names have floated into 
speculation encouraged by campaign stage managers 
two governors thompson of illinois and gov george deukmejian 
of california said they do not want to be considered as did sens 
nancy kassebaum of kansas and william armstrong of colorado i 
would be a liability protests sen al simpson of wyoming 
thompson cited family concerns he said hed have to travel too 
much and his wife couldnt come because they have a 10yearold in 
school 
at face value that would make him the first politician to 
shrink from seeking national office for want of a sitter 
if they wont run others will rep jack kemp of new york said 
hed be glad to accept sen dan quayle of indiana said it would be 
an honor sen pete domenici said he wasnt too proud to campaign a 
little for it howard baker says he doesnt want the job but it 
would be arrogant to turn it down 
mark them down for honest men the fact of the matter is that 
there arent many republican politicians who would say no if asked 
