<TEXT>
a leading newspaper on sunday criticized 
officials for banning superman and at least four chinese films 
that passed the censors and opened to packed movie houses 
in a rare plea from the official press the china youth news 
called for measures to prevent such lawlessness 
the report said superman was one of at least five movies 
banned in the capital since 1985 it said unidentified officials 
decided the films were unfit for the masses 
the officials had showings of superman halted in early 1986 
because they said the movie turned the world upside down and 
reversed the flow of time according to the report 
the officials did not want chinas youth to be inculcated with 
the films impossible idealism the report said 
in the 1978 movie superman rescues lois lane from death in an 
earthquake by circling the earth at the speed of light and 
reversing time 
two of the other films that were banned in beijing the fierce 
battle in taierzhuang and the beach have won awards in china 
the controversial taierzhuang depicts a battle between the 
kuomintang archrival to the communist party and japanese invaders 
in 1938 
in the movie the kuomintang who were forced out of china in 
1949 and now occupy taiwan are depicted as patriotic and even 
heroic an image which clashes sharply with the one created by the 
communist government 
the report said that in april 1987 when taierzhuang was 
playing across the nation officials closed the film in beijing 
after eight months of agitation in the movie industry the report 
said the government let the film show in beijing but only for six 
months and no advertising was allowed 
at the end of 1985 the report said the beach a explicit 
love story was suddenly pulled from beijing movie theaters even 
after official censors approved it the paper said certain 
leaders thought the plot would have a bad affect on society 
in the film a woman is forced by her family into an arranged 
marriage the scene of her wedding night portrays the tribulations 
of an unwilling bride in bed with her husband 
the paper said that in many cases the officials banning the 
films had no relation to the ministry of culture which is 
responsible for censorship it did not say what department of 
government the officials were from 
the report also said that since 1984 beijing has only allowed 
two copies each of popular martial arts movies to circulate in the 
capitals movie theaters while other cities had 10 copies 
this regulation might be a good one in order to limit the 
influence these movies have one young people the paper said 
but because theres no law to follow who knows whether its 
true 
the report said banning movies after they have already been 
released has cost beijings theaters thousands of dollars it also 
said officials who like unpopular movies have forced city film 
officials to order more copies of them causing further losses 
the report called for a law that would set clear regulations on 
the content of movies to counteract official capriciousness 
a recent issue of outlook magazine said officials at the 
ministry of culture are studying a proposed law setting censorship 
guidelines for movies 
among the topics being debated the magazine said is whether 
naked bodies or serious crimes should be depicted on chinas silver 
screen 
the proposal would mark the first time since communist china was 
established in 1949 that explicit standards have been set about 
what can and cannot be included in a chinese movie 
</TEXT>
