police and solidarity supporters clashed 
sunday after ceremonies marking the eighth anniverary of strikes 
that launched the now outlawed independent union federation 
witnesses said 
police moved in with truncheons against more than 100 
demonstrators as they marched for about 45 minutes through gdansks 
old town said a solidarity activist who spoke on condition of 
anonymity 
witnesses said a melee broke out after a chair was thrown into 
the line of security police as they attempted to block the marchers 
demonstrators then hurled tables and chairs from a nearby cafe 
as the helmeted riot police rushed the crowd 
about 20 young people were injured in the clash several 
seriously and a dozen were detained the solidarity spokesman said 
the staterun news agency pap in a dispatch late sunday said 
six police officers were injured in the clash which it said was 
touched off by demonstrators behaving in an extremely aggressive 
way 
it said the protesters chanted anticommunist slogans attacked 
police with rocks and demolished a cafe pap said the demonstrators 
also interrupted the peaceful activities at a nearby fair 
it gave no details about arrests or the number of injured 
demonstrators 
the clashes came after thousands attended a service at a nearby 
church marking the anniversary of the beginning of the 1980 strike 
after the services solidarity leader lech walesa spoke to 3000 
people who had gathered outside st brygidas church a solidarity 
stronghold 
our struggle is continuing walesa said we want to live 
in a better poland with more dignity 
walesa said solidarity leaders will meet on aug 28 in gdansk to 
discuss a text on the unions future 
walesa acknowledged that much had changed since 1980 and that 
there was no return to that period 
he said the union is now committed to evolutionary 
solutions rather than radical action 
witnesses said that after the gathering at the church marchers 
made their way to the center of town which was packed with 
visitors to a local fair 
the marchers shouted solidarity slogans and were joined by large 
numbers of passersby before security forces blocked their path 
witnesses said 
on friday 2000 shipyard workers and other solidarity 
supporters attended a ceremony marking the anniversary near the 
entrance to the lenin shipyard 
police watched that ceremony but did not move in 
at that ceremony walesa helped put wreaths and flowers on a 
monument erected to honor striking shipyard workers killed by 
security forces during labor unrest in 1970 
on aug 14 1980 workers in the lenin shipyards in gdansk began 
a strike over reinstating a fired crane operator two days later 
the demands grew to include an independent trade union and 
solidarity was born 
the union at its peak claimed about 10 million members or 
nearly onethird of the nations population 
the union was crushed when martial law was imposed in 1981 it 
was banned by parliament the next year 
