the soviet unions oncesecret blackjack 
bomber is an expanded version of americas b1b bomber according 
to the only us air force officer to have seen the giant soviet 
warplane 
maj gen gordon e fornell described the bomber in a story in 
sundays editions of the dayton daily news as being a close copy of 
the b1b from its pivoting wings to the rotary cruise missile 
launcher on its belly 
for years only the skimpiest details about the giant bomber 
were available outside the kremlin or defense department 
intelligence files 
the soviets allowed fornell and defense secretary frank c 
carlucci to take a close look at the plane on aug 2 while the two 
were on a fourday tour of soviet military bases soviet officials 
had earlier been allowed to climb aboard a b1b during a visit to 
ellsworth air force base in south dakota 
like the b1b the blackjack is designed to fly low and fast 
during longrange strategic bombing missions firing nucleartipped 
cruise missiles 
fornell a former bomber test pilot with more than 6000 flying 
hours in more than 40 types of aircraft and an adviser to carlucci 
said he believed there is evidence that the soviets copied at least 
the basic aerodynamic features of the b1b 
but he said it was impossible to tell during his 15minute 
inspection whether the blackjacks designers merely took advantage 
of public information on the b1b or profited from espionage 
its hard to determine not actually having flown the airplane 
or seen its actual combat capability what was done as far as the 
internal workings of their equipment he said 
even the crew assignments resemble the american bomber 
it has four crewmembers two pilots and what they described as 
an offensive systems operator and defense systems operator and 
the layout inside is very similar to that of the b1b he said 
