<TEXT>
orbiting space debris poses a threat to 
spacecraft and should be eliminated a national aeronautics and 
space administration scientist said sunday 
donald kessler a project scientist at nasas johnson space 
center told an international conference exploring various forms of 
space pollution that a particle could strike and damage a 
spacecraft the debris ranges in size from old nonfunctioning 
satellites and rocket boosters to nuts and bolts from 
disintegrating spacecraft 
kessler estimated that at least 48000 objects one centimeter or 
larger are in orbit about the earth but told a colloquium of the 
international astronomical union that the true number is probably 
much higher 
in june of 1983 a window of the space shuttle challenger was 
replaced after being struck by a piece of orbiting debris that 
caused a small pit later chemical analysis revealed the window 
had been hit by a fleck of paint no larger than one 
eightthousandth of an inch in diameter 
kessler says such collisions involving the space shuttle are 
rare because of the vehicles low orbit and the relatively short 
amount of time the shuttle spends in space longer space missions 
will require additional protection 
the problem gets to be more severe for something like the 
space station which is planned to be continuously there for 30 
years kessler said 
shields are currently being designed to protect the crew from 
debris about one centimeter in diameter the size of a marble 
the shields weigh an extra 2000 pounds per module there are 
six modules so thats an extra 12000 pounds of weight that are 
having to be put into orbit because of the orbital debris 
environment kessler said 
a presidential directive now requires that american spacecraft 
be designed to minimize the creation of space debris future rocket 
boosters said kessler will probably be designed to fall back to 
earth kessler estimated that redesigning boosters might increase 
their cost by 10 to 20 percent 
the us is not alone in recognizing the growing danger of space 
debris kessler said a 1986 explosion of a spent ariane rocket 
booster spewed 400 pieces of debris into orbit an event that 
woke the european space agency up to the problem of orbital 
debris 
</TEXT>
