<TEXT>
florida citrus merchandisers always 
protective of their highquality product are taking action to warn 
confused consumers they may be spending too much for dilutedjuice 
beverages 
deceptive labeling can cost consumers millions of dollars each 
year says robert behr economic research director for the 
florida department of citrus 
industry leaders are also asking the federal food and drug 
administration to implement rather than revoke a regulation 
requiring fruit and vegetable juice products to be clearly labeled 
to show the percentage of juice 
besides concern that consumers are confusing diluted products 
for real orange and grapefruit juice industry officials are 
reacting to growing competition from other juices and juicebased 
drinks 
for instance high prices and a poor consumer image have caused 
a precipitous decline in sales of 100percent grapefruit juice over 
the past decade orange juice too has lost some of its market 
share to apple juice and others plus the soft drinks that contain 
small amounts of fruit juices 
along with its modest consumerawareness campaign the citrus 
department is distributing new grapefruit juice television 
commercials a departure from recent years when such advertising 
was limited to newspapers and magazines 
in the past 100 percentpure grapefruit juice has been 
primarily advertised as a healthy wholesome product says 
department publicist cathy clay 
in addition to that we are now showing in the tv 
commercials that it is more refreshing invigorating uplifting 
she said 
the departments citrus marketing director william p gordon 
calls the 43 million 23week run of tv commercials beginning in 
midseptember a new approach to grapefruit juice advertising 
to increase topofmind awareness and meet the growing competition 
from other juices or juicebased beverages 
a recent study done for the citrus department showed that 40 
percent of the consumers questioned believed that a diluted 
grapefruit beverage was 100 percent pure juice 
the product advertised as a grapefruit cocktail contained less 
than 50 percent grapefruit juice and its label did not show that 
if only one person out of 10 mistakenly believes a certain 
product contains pure juice consumers could be overspending from 
50 million to 90 million a year depending on the amount of juice 
in that beverage behr said 
in some cases the consumers are actually paying more for a 
product that is not 100 percent juice even though that is what 
they believe they are getting he said 
few of the dilutedjuice beverages on grocery shelves have the 
juice content on their labels department officials say despite an 
fda regulation requiring such information 
the fruit and vegetable juice labeling rule has been on the 
fdas books for several years but it has never been implemented 
said the departments general counsel kristen chadwell 
and because of pressure from some industry groups the fda has 
declared its intent to revoke the rule ms chadwell said 
we of course have since sent them our objections to the 
revocation and provided them with our research results she said 
the fda is expected to decide which way to go by the end of the 
year 
the proliferation of juicebased drinks blends cocktails 
beverages and other variations with or without proper labeling 
information has stirred some consumer groups into action 
the ralph nader center for science in the public interest has 
called on the fda to crack down on manufacturers who do not list 
the percentage of juice contained in the products and the fda has 
been looking into false or misleading labels on some of the diluted 
beverages 
the fda does require that products sold as orange juice carry 
labels declaring the exact percentage of juice they contain 
florida industry people would like the same rule to apply to 
grapefruit juice eliminating at least that problem for the 
confused consumer 
</TEXT>
