<TEXT>
the united states should abandon farm price 
supports and production controls to capitalize on a growing demand 
by poorer nations for food an economics professor says 
us policy not only distorts us production away from its 
comparative advantage but contributes to the distortion of 
production decisions around the world said john m antle an 
associate professor of farm economics at the university of montana 
consequently the us share in commodity trade declines and 
the united states fails to exploit its comparative advantage he 
said 
antle released a study that predicts developed countries 
including some in east asia and latin america will be shipping 
more food to poor ones in coming years 
the fouryear study world agricultural development and the 
future of us agriculture was sponsored by the conservative 
american enterprise institute 
the report does not take into account the current drought in 
this country and others and its effect on reducing world food 
reserves 
eastern asia and latin america are likely to continue to 
experience high rates of growth in food production and 
subsaharan africa can be expected to continue to face stagnation 
and even reductions in food production and real income antle 
said 
the effect of these trends will be to increase further the 
trade in agricultural commodities especially cereals between 
developed and developing countries his report said 
the study predicted increased grain production in the united 
states and canada until at least the year 2000 the increase is 
greater than projected for 12 european nations that compete with 
the us but less than the projected increase for the soviet union 
and other communistruled countries in asia and latin america 
antle also predicted surpluses of millions of tons of major food 
crops in china east asia and southeast asia in the year 2000 
compared with deficits in 1980 but he forecasts continued or 
larger shortfalls for other parts of the third world 
antle also said some countries will remain poor even if they use 
their meager resources efficiently especially semiarid tropical 
regions in south central india northern and subsahara africa and 
parts of latin america 
most poorer countries will find it hard to increase their 
imports as singapore taiwan and south korea have done he said 
those three are small homogeneous and densely populated with low 
transport costs access to shipping lanes and have been able to 
make investments in human capital and institutions he said 
the future of chinas potential for increased supply and demand 
depends on its governments decisions antle added 
what does seem fairly certain is that east asia and the 
middleincome countries of latin america are particularly well 
positioned to take advantage of new technologies and new market 
opportunities he said 
</TEXT>
