<TEXT>
in beds of damp compost a web resembling 
angel hair forms tiny stems push out of the mulch and almost 
overnight swell into firm white mushrooms at one of the nations 
largest mushroom farms 
there are no caves or fields just 85 acres of sophisticated 
mushroom production under the roof at princeton farms in a rural 
section of bureau county 
this farm and a sister facility in zellwood fla both owned by 
lyon foods market about 32 million pounds of fresh mushrooms a 
year said princeton manager ralph scott 
its a blending of science and art scott said mushrooms 
are growing organisms and you have to handle them very carefully 
one popular mushroom misconception is that the sublime fungus 
grows only in the dark and with little attention he said 
production rooms at princeton are brightly lit and the annual 
payroll for the laborintensive business is 6 million 
the key to mushroom production is rich black soil blended from 
decomposed straw manure protein and peat moss 
each week 35 tractortrailer trucks arrive at the farm with 
straw shoveled out of horse stalls at chicagos racetracks steam 
rises from the long narrow piles as the pungent material 
decomposes producing temperatures of 160 degrees within the 
compost 
our success is here good compost makes good mushrooms 
scott said 
the straw is pasturized and protein from soybean peanut or 
cottonseed meal is blended into the compost to provide nutrients 
for the mushrooms 
the seed for the crop is mushroom spawn which is growing on 
millet or rye when it is purchased it is added to the straw and 
covered with peat moss and limestone 
the entire mixture is held in fourbysixfoot trays each eight 
inches tall 
the trays are stacked to the ceilings in 45 rooms that resemble 
huge walkin refrigerators temperature and humidity are carefully 
controlled at a cost of about 1 million a year said scott 
the spawn grow a web of fine white roots from which the 
mushrooms sprout workers gently spray them to maintain moisture 
it is just light watering like rain cascading onto the 
mushrooms not like putting two fingers over the hose nozzle and 
flooding it scott said 
it takes about 36 days for the crop to reach the harvest stage 
and picking is done over the course of a month 
about half the farms 425 employees are pickers many from 
mexico and asia and they gather 380000 pounds of mushrooms a 
week 
they climb up the trays pluck the biggest mushrooms from the 
mulch trim off the bottoms of the stems and place many of them 
directly into clear plastic baskets for supermarket display the 
less handling the less damage to the delicate mushrooms 
larger baskets are used for customers like restaurant operators 
lower quality mushrooms are sent to canning companies 
the harvest lands in customers hands within 24 hours said 
scott a 15year veteran of the mushroom business in addition to 
white and brown mushrooms princeton also distributes some 
specialty mushrooms like shiitake 
like any crop there are threats to the mushrooms a type of fly 
will eat the spawn too much water will cause discoloration a 
virus can wipe out production scott said technicians from the 
inhouse laboratory monitor 140 variables that can affect the 
harvest 
but improved varieties and growing techniques mean us mushroom 
growers now produce 650 million pounds a year scott said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

